# Extend HTML Element Props in Components

Every component must extend the native HTML element props it renders so callers can pass `className`, `onClick`, event handlers, `data-*` attributes, etc. without any extra wiring.

- Use `React.ComponentPropsWithoutRef<'element'>` (preferred) or `React.HTMLAttributes<HTMLElement>`
- Spread `...props` onto the root element
- Place custom props before `...props` so callers can still override

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — consumers cannot pass className, onClick, etc.
interface CardProps {
  title: string;
}
export function Card({ title }: CardProps) {
  return <div>{title}</div>;
}

// ✅ GOOD — extends div so all HTML div props work
interface CardProps extends React.ComponentPropsWithoutRef<'div'> {
  title: string;
}
export function Card({ title, className, ...props }: CardProps) {
  return (
    <div className={cn('rounded-lg p-4', className)} {...props}>
      {title}
    </div>
  );
}
```

Apply the same pattern for any element (`button`, `input`, `a`, `section`, etc.):

```tsx
interface ButtonProps extends React.ComponentPropsWithoutRef<'button'> {
  variant?: 'primary' | 'ghost';
}
```
